editorial_summary.overview: Music hall with original cast iron pillars, balcony and decor, staging an eclectic event programme.

reviews.text:
For a taste of what a 19th century music hall experience must have been like, the remarkable Wilton's is the place to go.
Its survival in the face of redevelopment is thanks to the dedication of people like John Betjeman. Its no frills repair is a masterclass in historic building conservation and it looks just right.
I was curious about how Mozart's Magic Flute could be staged in such a small auditorium and the answer, with just 10 performers and a solo piano accompaniment, was astonishingly well.
It was a thoroughly enjoyable performance in a wonderful building, and a great night out.

Wilton's Music Hall is the most amazing, wonderful venue. We went for the first time for the Potted Panto. Living in Brighton means we can only do London matinees. The venue was packed.
It is fascinating from the moment you go through that glorious front door. Rooms everywhere, bare brick walls, wonderful information about the music halls past and John Wilton himself.
The show was glorious and hilarious and chaotic and so much fun.
If you get the chance, go to Wilton's Music Hall ♥️♥️

An amazing little performance space tucked away in the back streets of East London. Beautifully restored and historically authentic in every way. Cosy, bare bricked bars and friendly staff. A visit for a show is a must.
Amazing historic and professional place. I've seen a lot of things here. Hidden away but definitely worth visiting.

Charming events space! We saw a Christmas  Panto here which was great but really loved the space. Has all the amenities and feel of a West End show venue but without the high prices and over-crowded feel. Several bars, comfy seating and great acoustics!!

editorial_summary.overview: Intimate Victorian concert venue for chamber music recitals and lunchtime concerts.

reviews.text:
World class music. World class snobbery.

We attended one of the late Sunday morning performances, which are perfectly timed for the weekend visitor. The music was absolutely exceptional. We enjoyed a flawless, virtuosic, performance in a venue with great acoustics.

However, the atmosphere was intimidating and represented everything that's bad about the British establishment. Not exactly the fault of the venue, but most of the other audience members fell firmly into the pale and stale category and were unwelcoming at best, and downright rude at worst. Thankfully, the music (did I mention how good the music was?), just about compensated.

We went to see international pianist Girma yifrashewa. We enjoyed listening to his own pieces. Also played the legendary Ethiopian female pianist and composer Emahoy Tsegué-Maryam Guèbrou's pieces. Full House audience applause 👏🏼 🙌🏽 👌

Wigmore Hall is one of the best recital halls anywhere. Large enough to have serious talent perform, but small enough that even the seats right at the back and in the balcony have excellent acoustics.
Add to that a good location, decent bar and seats that can accommodate the widest of bottoms and it's a winner.

I am a wigmore member. I recently tried purchasing the newly released concert tickets yesterday to realise that the “10am” ticket release was open for ticketing at “9.57-9.58am”

Well this could be an internal error in their system is a good thing for us? I guess so.

I proceeded to book several concert tickets for my partner & I on the last few rows that were the cheapest at 18£, including the likes of Uchida, Schiff and a few more

As i proceeded to checkout 15mins later, i was faced with a 5min wait to get past to entering my card details before the website crashed with ERROR 404, upon reloading i realised my basket was EMPTY which should NOT be the case.

In my past experiences there is a 30min grace period in the checkout basket before u are prompted to “EXTEND” or else ticket selection WILL BE cancelled

However upon reloading, tickets i chose were gone! Impossible init? When one selected the tickets how is someone else able to buy?

I wrote an email to the box office but they did not make a reply to me or issue an apology

1) for releasing the tickets at 2mins BEFORE stated 10am

2) for addressing the technical issue i face of losing my selected tickets despite them in my basket! Is quite awful to face this issue as a member of wigmore!
Just been to another fabulous Sunday concert. Wonderful, moving performance by the Aquinas piano trio. Balm to the soul! Thank you Wigmore.

name: Foyles
address: 107 Charing Cross Rd, London WC2H 0EB, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Large, multi-genre bookstore spread over 5 floors, also selling CD/DVDs, plus jazz cafe and events.

details.formatted_address: 107 Charing Cross Rd, London WC2H 0EB, UK
details.name: Foyles

reviews.text:
A true paradise for book lovers, Foyles on Charing Cross Road feels like stepping into a world built entirely from words and imagination. Spread across several bright, airy floors, it offers an incredible range — from classics and poetry to rare finds and beautiful stationery.
The vibe is peaceful but inspiring; you can easily lose track of time exploring its endless shelves. The in-house café adds a perfect touch, inviting you to sit with a coffee and your new reads.
Foyles isn’t just a bookstore — it’s a London institution, and every visit feels a little like coming home.

I adore coming here. There's several floors and a cafe at the top. I wish there were more seats around the book store.

It's usually bustling and yet I find it a calming oasis to escape to when I need a break from the city.

Coming here reminds me of the days when there were Borders book shops. Idk why I get those vibes.

I always discover books that remind me how wondrous and magical the literature world is, rich with knowledge and a feast for the mind.

Foyles is a paradise for book lovers! The selection is incredible, covering all genres across multiple floors. The space is bright and welcoming, making it a great place to browse for hours. Plus, the Cafe upstairs is a nice spot to sit and read!

The organization and easy to shop format of the books and merchandise was excellent. Thisnwas a destination for me and a colleague, both extreme book lovers, and this was a fun store. I could have spent hours more here. It was very contemporary and even the Cafe was  great. The check out stand employees were extremely kind and made great suggestions. I look forward to a return trip!

It's always... always a pleasure walking into Foyles Charing Cross. I've been going to this HQ branch on and off since 2003 - long before its refurbishment.🪄

These days, I visit straight off the bus to quickly browse or pop in specially to collect my book order.

Staff are consistent in their customer service - zen, helpful, & knowledgeable ✨️

Upstairs on the 5th floor is a spacious and bustling café where customers flock to for conversations, coffee & cake, or 'working from anywhere'!☕️🍰🥐💻

Even the lift experience feels like an extension of the Foyles brand - efficient, clean & spacious.

Hopefully, these photos from my recent visit give you a sense of my description above. 😊

Enjoy your experience! 📚

name: BFI IMAX
address: 1 Charlie Chaplin Walk South Bank, London SE1 8XR, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Movie theater chain known for presenting 3D films on a giant screen, including blockbusters.

details.formatted_address: 1 Charlie Chaplin Walk South Bank, London SE1 8XR, UK
details.name: BFI IMAX

reviews.text: It's got a very posh feeling to it. The ground floor lounge and cafe is very nice. The coffee wasn't surprisingly overpriced. The underground pass was hard to find. I wish there were bigger signs out on the main road. The screen is surprisingly big. It was my first experience. But my seat wasn't very good..the lower you are the worse the experience. So it is recommended that you get the higher seats. Recording inside the theatre is not allowed. They are very strict about that.

Was a little hard to find the entrance to the place and itis isolated from the rest of the world and can be accessed by the underground walkways.

Caffe downstairs was very good and the toilets were cleen.

Movie theatre was very large and a huge screen.

Perfect way to experience 15/70mm Print.. got to experience “Sinners” in its most definitive way. With a surprise special appearance from the films stars Michael B Jordan and Wunmi Mosaku

Will definitely be returning for future 70mm print experiences

Watched Re-release of Interstellar on the occasion of 10th anniversary. What can I say, a Nolan brothers masterpiece. I watched it in a normal theatre 10 years ago and throughout this screening, I can't help but wonder, how much impact this movie has when watched on IMAX. The detailing was perfect. I want to take this opportunity to say this is one of the 2 70mm IMAX screens in London, other being Science Museum where I watched Oppenheimer. Although this is just a single laser while Science Museum is dual laser, I felt this screen and Sound had a greater impact than Science Museum. I loved the overall impact of watching the movie here and I'm so happy now.
PS: The Underground tunnel from waterloo station is no clear navigation, Google maps gave me a good tour of Waterloo. So be careful.

As pricey as the ticket might be, if you're looking for a HUGE screen and incredible sound experience then do just come! A nice spacious environment, quite easy to get to from Waterloo. Has a coffee shop and bar inside on ground floor (with Ben & Gerrys parlour), with ice cream and sweets upstairs. Lots of people choose the middle seats which I get but I have always sat in the side blocks and have never been disappointed. Quite good legroom (I'm 6ft 1). Seats are comfortable.

editorial_summary.overview: Elegant church with a cafe in the vaulted crypt and regular concerts and lunchtime music recitals.

reviews.text:
Exquisite historic church, completed in 1726, replacing a Tudor church that previously stood on the same site.
The design, by James Gibbs, has become one of London's most recognisable churches. It's well worth a look inside, where beautiful ceiling decorations, ornately detailed columns and galleries create an impression of space.
The church's interior has a light, airy feel, and provides a place of calm to escape the crowds and bustle of the city streets.
St Martin-in-the-Fields has a long history of helping in the fight against homelessness, and still holds regular services. The church is free to visit but donations are welcomed to support the upkeep of the building.

St Martin-in-the-Fields is an iconic Anglican church located in Trafalgar Square. Renowned for its stunning neoclassical architecture, it offers a peaceful refuge amid the city’s hustle. The church hosts regular concerts and art exhibitions, enhancing its cultural significance. A visit provides a blend of history, spirituality, and artistic expression, making it a must-see destination for tourists and locals alike.

Beautiful church - I came in last year with my Grandmother to see the church, and we had a coffee in the crypt which was a lovely atmosphere. We were hoping to see some famous epitaphs that were reportedly held at St Martins, and managed to find them stacked up in storage (after climbing over some boxes and stacked tables!). I then came again for the Christmas eve carol service 2024, which was an incredible experience and quite emotional. I’d hugely recommend this to anyone either living in London or visiting for Christmas!

Wonderful historic church in great location right next to Trafalgar Square. The church was designed by James Gibbs (1682-1754) and its influence can be seen in many churches in the New World, such as Saint Michael's Church in Charleston SC and Christ Church in Philadelphia. Beautiful interior. The church gave its name to the famous eponymous orchestra, the Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields, most famous for its many legendary recordings under Sir Neville Marriner (1924-2016). We were fortunate to see a recent performance with the orchestra of Bach's St. John's Passion at the church.

Lovely place for candlelight piano concert. It’s becoming such a great escape from the day-to-day busyness and so good for the soul to listen to incredible music in an equally incredible place - gothic, historic, so full of reflective energy! Come and feel it for yourself!

name: Scandinavian Kitchen
address: 61 Great Titchfield St., London W1W 7PP, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Grocery stocking 600+ traditional and gourmet foods from Sweden, Norway, Denmark and Finland.

details.formatted_address: 61 Great Titchfield St., London W1W 7PP, UK
details.name: Scandinavian Kitchen

reviews.text:
Really delicious open sandwiches & salads- perfect for a quick office lunch or meeting.

The open sandwiches are the best, if you like rye bread, and the perfect amount- a bargain if you take them away too. Veggie, meat & fish options.

The salad & sandwich deal is also great value, just beware, the salads can make the rye bread pretty soggy & disintegrate if you are travelling back to the office far as they’re all boxed together.

Great options, good coffee. Though they are definitely made by the variety and taste of their open sandwiches (and salads) which are amazing all super fresh and full of flavour. Nice interior though sometimes it is harder to get a table.

I liked the place outside, cozy street, but I think inside needs improvement as there wasn’t enough space to move at some point. Luckily the weather was good enough to sit on the lovely bench outside and to enjoy Scandinavian.
I would suggest to visit early, as at 2 pm on Sunday they were already out of some menu positions.
Downstairs there’s a small store where you can get anything you like.
I definitely liked service and the taste of food.
Probably will visit again.

I have been here many years before, when there was completely different layout to the whole shop. Now there is a seating in the back and a shop downstairs. I have not given this five stars, Due to quite an unfriendly set up as you walk into the shop. it is difficult to see all that is on offer through the glass and by looking at some of the food you’re at the front of the queue and in the way of other people and feel rushed. The staff are fine but you feel you are in their way by looking at the produce.
Seating seems quite uncomfortable, with little stools here and there.
There is a toilet downstairs which is very clean and good.
I have given the food 1 star due to quite extortionate prices. This is not Sweden… I think £4.50 for Semla in London is £1 overpriced at least.
as a London Swede, I appreciate this place so much! makes me feel very much at home

editorial_summary.overview: Chain cinema for a wide range of entertainment, including the latest releases & live event screenings.

reviews.text: This has always been on my list of cinemas to go to. As a film professional I got to say, Screen 1 here is probably one of the best cinema experiences you can have in London. due to it being made by Dolby from the ground up.  Sound and picture is really impressive. Dolby vision and atmosphere perfection. Highly recommend

This is a gem in the Odeon cinema chain. A luxury cinema with only a few screens, about 2-4 floors underground and very quiet.

We have the lay back reclining seats with the plus option. The plus option gives optimal positioning for the Dolby sound system and this made a massive difference. You can really feel the audio when watching the movie.

There are buttons for reclining and a lovely table to put your snacks and refreshments on. Staff are polite and toilets relatively clean.

We would definitely come back again just for a great experience to watch in a nice venue. Price is worth it but is more than you’d ever pay in another cinema, even regular Odeons.

Best recliners in London. Best audio in London. It’s my go-to cinema. Bar queue is a chaos, always a chaos. Half of the time they just never got me the nachos and had to chase people for refund. Nevertheless, the screen time experience is great.

We have visited it over the weekend. The cinema goes deeply underground. The rooms are quite large with comfortable seating. This is likely the best cinema in Leicester Square. I would say that the downside are the small and not as clean toilets that cannot support the demand of the end of a screening session.

A great experience! Went to watch transformers here in Dolby and it was an experience like never before!!! The sound was breathtaking, great volume and quality and the rumble from the subwoofers can actually be felt. The screen quality next level as well but the screen was a bit small when sat at the very back of the theatre but overall a 10/10 experience. The staff were great and the look of the place was unique.

editorial_summary.overview: Secondhand camera shop beside the British Museum serving tea, coffee and sandwiches.

reviews.text:
I came across this museum by accident when looking for things to do in London and was not disappointed. It is a must visit for anyone interested in photography. The entry fee is 3 Eur, to be paid after the visit. There is also a cafe and a toilet.
It can also be a fun place for kids who are interested in photography, since they have a few interactive games as well. The museum itself is quite small and you can see everything in 15-20 minutes.

Cute, small cafe with a museum of old film cameras in the basement. Reasonably priced coffees and small pastries are served and it costs £3 to visit the museum downstairs.

They also offer some camera repair services and sell old camera parts. It’s a good visit for photography/camera enthusiasts!

After reading several reviews, I visited the Camera Museum, and it exceeded my expectations.
The ground floor houses a stylish café, and you descend a steep staircase, giving it a secretive feel. The museum itself is filled with fascinating historical cameras, and the atmosphere is wonderfully nostalgic.

Although I had a poor connection which delayed my payment for the entrance fee, the staff were incredibly patient and handled the situation with kindness, showing no irritation.

It was a unique and enjoyable experience, especially for photography enthusiasts.

A very interesting place for any photographer, professional or amateur, to visit.

Enjoyed a cold ale in the café bar, then spent the best part of an hour exploring the museum downstairs.

Friendly, amusing staff! Will be back.

Amazing little museum about cameras, Tucked within the lower level of a charming cafe, this camera museum gives visitors a small snapshot of photographic history. The whole place is a quirky combination of a coffee shop, camera store, and museum.

The lower two rooms are packed with different types of cameras, some of which you can even pick up and hold. The various models basically form a timeline of photographic technology, with cameras dating from the 1800s—the advent of photography—up until the modern digital age.

London's Camera Museum began after one of the cafe’s owners, who happened to be an avid camera collector, decided to open his own small camera shop in the same space where customers enjoyed their coffee and sweets. He later incorporated pieces from his collection into the space, forming the museum.

Even the upstairs cafe shows hints of the collection waiting down below. Photography-themed paraphernalia covers the walls, which patrons can admire while snacking on cookies and cakes. There’s also a small camera repair shop at the site as well.

editorial_summary.overview: Grand French art deco restaurant with classic brasserie dishes and choucroutes in 1930s building.

reviews.text: This is probably one of the best restaurants I've ever been to, from the easily accessible and obvious location, to the bright smile goodbye from the barrister. This place has one of the most eye catching atmospheres I've ever seen, such uniqueness with the jazz band to set the tone, and a quite French looking colour tone, very very exquisite. The server Muhammad SW did his job amazingly, he kindly explained the menu to us, what options are available, what he would recommend and translated the menu for us as we don't speak french. 😂 This table service really foreshadowed the excellence of the food thus to come, Food was out of this world good, very connected to their culture as in the "frenchness" haha, and was cooked perfectly. But it only got better as I was BLOWN away by the desserts, they really came out with a whole trolley full of cheese, 😍 something you'll see out of your food dreams. And I don't know how they do it but their goats cheese taste better than any other goats cheese I've tasted before. ultimately this  restaurant portrays fine dining at it's absolute peak. You want an outrageous atmosphere, come here. You want great service, come here. And you want mouth watering food, come here. I really couldn't ask for more for my birthday with my family. 110% recommended coming here at least once in your lifetime. 🙌😁👍🏾

I’ve never tried French food before. What a great introduction. Has French onion soup, it was very hearty. The beef bourguignon was absolute class. Rich and delicious and the beef just melted in your mouth. Also had the floating island dessert- it’s light and not overly sweet to perfectly end the meal.

I can honestly say this is the best restaurant I’ve ever been to. Just wow.
You cannot get such an atmosphere and good food even in Paris (Paris doesn’t even come close).
Everything was impeccable.
The building is so beautiful, there was live music, spacious and comfortable sitting, the ambiance was amazing, and the food absolutely phenomenal!
My party was French and they said the food was outstanding.
I cannot recommend this place enough. It really is worth the splurge.

The food was absolutely amazing! The steak haché is definitely worth the hype. The Merlot we had with the dishes was delicious, and the meals were not only tasty but also affordable. Great value for money in a beautiful setting. For a three-course meal and a few bottles of red wine, we paid less than £70 per person for a group of four. The live jazz band really added to the experience. The only downside was that the floors were quite slippery, which caused both the staff and guests to slip from time to time. Otherwise, it was an amazing experience. A must-do!

Amazing art decor style architecture, I have my annual birthday meal at Zedel. Great food and great atmosphere. Some live music if you come on the right time. Just amazing atmosphere and experience. We had the Choucroute Royal to share. Generous portion and reasonable prices. One of my favourite French restaurant in London. You will never have a bad meal here.
Staffs are friendly and helpful.
Booking in advance advisable especially during peak. I have never seen this restaurant not busy.
Nearest tube - Piccadilly Circus
Parking - available
Toilet - available ( even the toilet look great)

editorial_summary.overview: Smoothies, cocktails and Cuban dishes in a cafe with an outdoor street food counter and live music.

reviews.text: A truly great dining experience. Querky, interesting and very delicious. The food is amazing. Great cocktails ( we had a Habana) and beer. Really interesting decor with lots of historical pictures. Great music. Nice friendly staff and very attentive. Oh and did I mention the food? Wow, beautifully balanced spices with tasty dips and sauces. We had a sharing platter and Prawns with rice and plantain. Sooo nice. Highly recommended by a retired chef. Enjoy.
Loved this place! The food was full of flavour, the vibe was fun, and Bryan was really lovely and helpful. Smoothie was great too. Would 100% go back!

It looks more like a bar than a restaurant, so I’ve never got around to visit. It turns out, they are open in the daytime, and their food is good.

I had Tortilla (omlette), Quimbobo (Okra stew), and a bowl of black beans. Yes, it was probably more than I needed, but everything was delicious.
The decor is bear and everything screams boozy bar. I felt out of place, but I would happily go back there for lunch when there is no loud music and drunken people.
This place is one of the best if not the best latin bars in London. The music is authentic and the DJs know how to get the crowd going. Five star entertainment.

We are from Portugal and visiting London atm. We came across your lovely restaurant, nice decoration and good vibes. To our suprise the girl that serve us is from Portugal too. Her name is Ana and her service was excellent she was really friendly and we had a really nice chat. Hopefully we visit again before we leave. 5 stars

editorial_summary.overview: Library containing the Magna Carta and handwritten Beatles lyrics on some 400 miles of shelves.

reviews.text: An incredible place. It is a public working/study place plus a museum. It's quite busy and hard to find a table. However the atmosphere was great. I enjoyed my time working here. It is also possible to have a reader card which is valid for 3 years. The application process was quick and easy. Lovely staff!

I loved the place and the collection of rare books like Shakespeare or magna carta. I would love the information point to be more helpful however. I had to find out what to do from different places. Also the daily library was cancelled because there was a private booking... and there wasn't enough guides... so basically whoever pays more wins. Also to get to any reading rooms you must have a library card. If you live in the UK you need a driving licence, otherwise an ID and proof of address is needed. It's really nice and quiet in the reading rooms.

Went for both ‘A Silk Road Oasis’ and ‘Medieval Women’ exhibition. The Life in ancient Dunhuang is fascinating. With a lot of Buddhist Scriptures and ancient documents/ some early woodblock prints. The Medieval women exhibition was interesting and inspiring, to learn what women have achieved despite all the challenges.
Lovely space.
Nearest Tube stations- King’s Cross, Euston and Euston Square.
Cloakroom- available
Cafe - available
Toilet - available

The British Library is a book lover's paradise! Stunning architecture, vast collections, and a peaceful atmosphere make it a perfect spot for research, reading, or simply getting lost in the world of books. Highly recommend!

Interesting place to spend a peaceful time reading. Good to see the free museum pieces such as the Magna Carta, original Beatles lyrics, Shakespeare items etc but many of the items were removed from display when I visited recently.  Nice little cafe and bookshop too.

editorial_summary.overview: Fair-trade coffee & gourmet treats in the cafe & whole or freshly ground beans bagged to take home.

reviews.text: Not worth the wait if queue is long. Excellent coffee. Limited seating and a lot more standing  space. Where it’s located, food is amazing for price. Wonderfully environmentally conscious with reusable cups having a deposit of £5 but you can return them. Service was efficient however.

The place was heaving! So busy, so popular and so worth it.

The staff were really friendly and worked really quickly to manage the large line that had developed. They have a no single use cup system which is nice. Grabbed a great long black, really strong flavour.

They had run out of almond croissants and it was relatively early in the day so I’d recommend going early, we got the Pain au chocolat which was incredible. Great layers, buttery flavour. Completely worth it.

Would highly recommend.

Tried their flat white (amazing) with some pistachio financier. A great combination for me. There was a line but moved pretty quickly. Limited space of seating and also there is a fee for to go cup so be prepared. Definitely will come back for the flat white.

This chain coffee shop is located inside Borough Market and is fairly easy to find, although it often has long lines. The shop is small, so seating is limited. I heard from friends that their coffee is quite good, so I decided to give it a try. I ordered a latte and a pain au chocolat, and both were enjoyable. Notably, the barista calls out the customer’s order before preparing the latte art right in front of them, which adds a nice touch. The staff were also very polite. Additionally, there was a warning on the tables for customers to be cautious with their belongings due to the presence of pickpockets in the market. I’ll definitely come back to try other items!

As lovely as it was crowded, and it was very crowded.
The matcha cookie is not from them (there are 50 places to get really good pastries within 50 yards), and I was politely asked not to eat it there (completely understandable, but I've been told - sternly- that 2 pieces of pastry are to much).
Despite that (and the crowd, oh, the crowd!), it was a great experience. Pay them a visit if you're in the Borough Market.

name: Rich Mix
address: 35-47 Bethnal Grn Rd, London E1 6LA, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Community arts hub staging music, dance and spoken word performance, art shows and film screenings.

details.formatted_address: 35-47 Bethnal Grn Rd, London E1 6LA, UK
details.name: Rich Mix

reviews.text:
I recently attended a Dang Show concert at Rich Mix, and the experience was absolutely incredible. The venue itself is vibrant, welcoming, and full of creative energy. Located in the heart of East London, just a short walk from Shoreditch High Street station, Rich Mix is an arts and culture hub that brings together people from all backgrounds through music, film, performance, and community events.
😊🙏🙏
The performance space was intimate yet spacious, offering excellent acoustics and clear sightlines from every seat. The Dang Show concert was phenomenal—moving, soulful, and rich in cultural expression. The atmosphere was electric, and the staff were friendly, professional, and well-organised, making the evening smooth and enjoyable from start to finish.

Rich Mix hosts a diverse programme of events throughout the year, including live music, independent films, spoken word, theatre, and community workshops. It’s a space that celebrates global voices and supports both emerging and established artists, with a strong emphasis on inclusivity and creativity.

Whether you're looking to attend a captivating concert, explore meaningful exhibitions, or participate in thought-provoking talks and workshops, Rich Mix has something for everyone. It’s not just a venue, it’s a community-driven cultural institution that adds real value to London’s creative landscape.

I highly recommend visiting Rich Mix. My evening with Dang Show was unforgettable, and I look forward to returning soon for more inspiring events. If you're passionate about the arts and culture, this is a must visit spot in London.

I went to Rich Mix for a show, and it was a fantastic experience! Beyond the performance itself, I was really impressed by the range of cultural programming they have coming up. From independent film screenings and live music to thought-provoking talks, exhibitions, and community events, it’s clear that Rich Mix is an important space for the arts in London. Located in the heart of Shoreditch, it brings together diverse voices and creative talent, making it a vital hub for both emerging and established artists.

On top of that, the security and staff were super helpful—you can tell they really care about the space and the people who visit. Definitely a place worth supporting!

I live near by and have been going to Richmix multiple times a month for the past 2 years. Every time I’ve been there I’ve had a great experience. From the cinema experience to the community events, it’s all a lot of fun. The staff are also amazing and friendly.

Rich Mix is a vibrant cultural hub in the heart of Shoreditch, offering a fantastic range of events and experiences. The venue is beautifully designed, with a modern and inviting atmosphere that makes it perfect for a night out or a casual visit. Whether you’re attending a live music performance, a film screening, or an art exhibition, there’s always something exciting happening. The staff are friendly and welcoming, and the variety of food and drink options adds to the overall experience. Rich Mix truly stands out as a cultural gem in London, providing something for everyone.
Quality cultural space with a variety of events, exhibitions, cinema, arts and music.

name: Kaffeine
address: 66 Great Titchfield St., London W1W 7QJ, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Independent Aussie/Kiwi-owned coffee shop with deli-style breakfasts, sandwiches and salads.

details.formatted_address: 66 Great Titchfield St., London W1W 7QJ, UK
details.name: Kaffeine

reviews.text: Lovely small cafe tucked away a few minutes behind the busy Oxford circus. Coffee was ok very small cup, personally wished it was served warmer . They offer a limited selection of baked sweet treats, and they do serve a few breakfast dishes.

As an Australian who works in the cafe scene back home I had very high hopes for Kaffeine. Unfortunately, it did not meet those hopes.

Let's get the positives out of the way first. The wait staff were lovely and accommodating (more on that later), the food was downright delicious and the treat selection was incredible. If you're going here for a feed I cannot recommend it enough.

Now the one negative thing: the coffee. Mine and my partner's coffee was downright undrinkable. Genuinely the worst coffee I've ever had.  Bitter and sour with a terrible after-taste that you couldn't wash out. That being said, when I raised this with staff they promptly made a remake free of charge. My second coffee was (by London standards) great! It was hands down the best coffee I've had in London. However, by the standards of an Australian cuppa (which is how this place bills itself) it was pretty average. The coffee was still bitter, albeit only very slightly, and lacked any body. I understand the coffee scene is wildly different in London but as a cafe that markets as Australian, I wouldnt say it lived up to that.

(The pancakes were amazing though!!!)

Decent cafe
Good Desert and some nice brunch option.

Just for suggestion:hope they add more great cakes like burnt cheese cake or blueberry /strawberry cheese cake

Nice coffee. The iced oat milk latte was sensational with the glass. The iced americano was pretty strong which was my favourite style.  They have two tables of benches outside. It was a sunny morning, so we sat outside!
Took a coffee to go and it was really good! The food looked amazing and it is a good stop for breakfast if you are in the area.

editorial_summary.overview: Three-screen cinema with a bar & cafe.

reviews.text:
We went to watch Warfare (which is a must watch!)
The cinema is nice, with a cute caffe inside and good film selection. But quite expensive

I can’t believe I was asked to leave when I was sitting in the cafe area, having a pain au chocolate quickly for my lunch, before going to watch the movie in the auditorium in a few minutes. I love Curzon. I love movies. I am a cult member. I have been to many other better theaters and cinemas, and sometimes I was having a bread and coffee as my lunch or dinner when I was sitting in a table where you can order food or drinks from them. I was never told off by anyone because I was not having food or drinks from there. Firstly, I was there to get ready for watching a movie or play, which is the main purpose. I wouldn’t randomly go to a restaurant and have a meal prepared by myself. Secondly, customers are not buying the drinks or food you are offering, because they don’t like the food or drinks you are selling. I was forced to leave and I went to the auditorium to try to have my lunch but the auditorium was smelly. It was so cruel that you don’t let a customer sitting in a table for just a few minutes to let them have their lunch before watching the movie. I was so disappointed about this.

amazing! top floor is a cafe that is hangout out even on a non movie outing. the floor below is a cool bar and lounge area. same applies; a place i’d check out without a movie. last bottom floor is the movie theater. great big screens with clean comfy seats. great selection of movies. i heard they have great deals and events that lots of film fans would appreciate. great cinema!

My very favourite cinema in London!

Upstairs is a cool bar, serving drinks and artisans snacks.

Downstairs are the cinemas, lined with photos of stars at Curzon movie premiers etc.

Picture and movie quality is always great, and they have more of the sort of movies I like: arty, intellectual, awarding winning, foreign language movies.

I pay a monthly membership and so worth it.

Pictures attached are outfits from the Poor Things, displayed at the cinema.

We really enjoyed the preview screening of The Blue Road: The Edna O'Brien Story last night.
Had an issue at the venue, and the management were very supportive and responsive in resolving it. Recommended.

editorial_summary.overview: Cheery, Australian-style cafe serving coffee, breakfast, small plates, wine, beer & weekend brunch.

reviews.text:
Lovely place with a very tasty menu. I really enjoyed my dish (adabo pork) and got a taste of the fried chicken french toast which was also amazing.

Even though I found it expensive (as everything in London) I feel that it was worth it. The dishes were exceptional and different than other brunch/breakfast places.

A really interesting place which I will probably visit again.

A lovely spot for lunch and tucked away. I had the avocado toast with halloumi and really enjoyed it—fresh and flavorful. The iced matcha latte was well prepared with a whisk. The staff were friendly, though service was on the slow side (although it was lunch time so they were busy), so I wouldn’t recommend it if you're in a rush. The only downside was the carrot cake, which I found a bit dry.
Overall, I would definitely come back.

A fantastic little breakfast spot with a buzzing atmosphere using fresh quality ingredients. The coffee is also great. Two breakfasts and coffee will come to around £55ish so it’s a bit pricey, then again central London. I found the full English (forgot the proper name) and the chorizo hash to be oily but that’s what some might expect for a breakfast, that’s me being picky. Tasted great and service was very helpful and smiley.
Excellent breakfast and great staff! Had the pear and blackberry french toast and smashed avo with salmon.  Several people were turned away while we ate so be sure to make a reservation.

I quite enjoyed the food to be honest, and the chips were delicious! The hot drink however was a bit disappointing. I order a chai and it tasted more like hot milk, whereas my friend ordered a latte and she said it didn’t feel like there was any coffee in there. But otherwise the food is delicious!

editorial_summary.overview: London's oldest French restaurant offering fine-dining classics in a grand Georgian townhouse.

reviews.text:
@lescargotsoho is the oldest French restaurant in London, and the vibes really showed it. Service was super friendly (thanks to the waiter who tried to take really nice photos of us) and we had a pleasant time.

Of course the escargots were my absolute favorite and is a must order. The other dishes were alright and didn’t particularly stand out. Linguine was good but the risotto was unfortunately too salty so I couldn’t finish the whole thing.

A great place - truly a piece of Paris in London.

The food is fabulous and most of all the staff are incredible professional and kind. The atmosphere is nice and elegant.

The wine collection is phenomenal, a reason to visit on its own.

We only had ‘snacks’ and wine, and wish to have had more. The truffle and pecorino nuts are recommended

A very enjoyable Sunday Lunch at the renowned L'Escargot restaurant.
An elegant venue designed in the classic French Brasserie style.
The menu is French and European.
The food was excellent as was the service and the ambience.
An ideal venue for a special occasion and dining with friends and family.

I recently dined at Escargot in London, known for its authentic French flavours and the food was absolutely fantastic! If they offer you bread, definitely take it, the fresh French bread and cheese are a must-try! The atmosphere was pleasant but I found the service a bit lacking.

Overall, a great spot for the cuisine, but there’s room for improvement in hospitality.

Overall: ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️

An easy 5 star sweep across the board for Brian Clivas’s Soho institution L’Escargot. Delightful service and delicious French food served in a warm, beautifully inviting setting nestled in the beating heart of Soho’s Greek Street.

At the time of writing there is an excellent value lunch menu at £20 for two courses and £25 for three. It doesn’t get better in Central London.

This is somewhere you’ll want to revisit time and time again.

Bonus that it’s dog friendly!

Food: French

What I liked:

• Top notch Service
• Stunning interior
• Perfectly portioned, beautifully presented food
• Great price point

What I didn’t like:

• N/A

Do I recommend going? YES
Will I go again? YES
Was it good value? YES
Price Point: $$

editorial_summary.overview: 2-screen arthouse cinema focused on independent and foreign films, with royal boxes and a bar.

reviews.text: We were in cinema room 1 which is not like the other pictures you see on reviews. The seats are worn which stains. There are no tables or cup holders to put drinks and snacks so you hold everything or put them on the floor. We even paid extra for the seats we had but really was not worth it. Very much needs new seat covers and a makeover. The staff were nice tho
Unique cinema screen. Relaxing and quiet atmosphere on Saturday afternoon. Will come back. Love the decor in the cinema

I went to The Return Q&A event on 10th April 2025. To be honest, this movie was scary for me because it contains a lot of blood and killing. I wouldn’t stay if there wasn’t a section of Q&A after the screening. In Q&A section what shocked me was that after I asked my question to a famous actor. The host was interrupting and said that she had got a few other questions from other people, trying to stop me. At the end of my question, I was asking if I could record the actor’s answer for my main questions, so I could listen to it again. I think this was a considerate question to ask for actor’s permission. Because the actor mentioned in an interview that she doesn’t want to be filmed in a daily life. I don’t know why the host was misunderstanding my question and interrupted me. I am grateful for such wonderful chances that Curzon created for audiences, but Please have a better host in Q&A section! The host must be patient and professional. (I would try to talk to the actor I admire before the screening, if I knew the host in Q&A section would destroy my experience.)

The behaviour and attitude of the two ‘managers’ at the Twiggy Q&A screening today was shameful and somewhat ruined what would have been a great day. The other staff were all fine and it’s a nice cinema but this is it for me now with the Curzon Mayfair sadly.

TOP GUN 2 - MAVERICK ! Brilliant!

We hadn’t been before, typically regulars at Everyman but times didn’t work so Curzon we went.

Great central location, fab entrance area, and screen 1 is a very cool space. Love the height of the ceiling and the detail. Seats are super comfy.

Tasty snack BUT, why hot chocolate is served in a take away cup and not a proper mug!

editorial_summary.overview: Wood and marble line this light-flooded brasserie for European cuisine in a grand 1930s institute.

reviews.text:
Great building!
But the library, why I haven’t been there  before?
Entrance is free just bring an ID.

Spectacular building inside and out, the Royal Institute of British Architects (RIBA) was designed by Grey Wornum (1888-1957). The building is reminiscent of the Stockholm Public Library by Gunnar Asplund (1885-1940) in a subdued neoclassical style (and Art Deco on the inside). Great library and wonderful architecture bookstore.
One of the finest examples of art deco, huge marble columns support a giant atrium bathed in light from immense windows. A must see and free entry too.

Came here to visit the institute and also to see an exhibition of the 2019 Royal Gold Medal winner, Sir Nicolas Grimshaw. Several exhibits showcase examples of his work along with descriptions, models and examples of architectural structures to help explain things further.

The building itself is an nice example of Art Deco, but in a style very sympathetic to the surrounding fine buildings along Portland Place.

Firstly they had no idea whom the person receiving their goody bag was.
Secondly they go and put their drinking table in front of the RIBA's Mural.
Especially when they had plenty of space to put the table elsewhere.

editorial_summary.overview: Elegant restaurant serving Modern European food & afternoon tea with grand, art deco glamour.

reviews.text: Our visit to The Wolseley was absolutely wonderful. From the moment we arrived, the atmosphere felt elegant yet welcoming. We enjoyed a lovely brunch, followed later by afternoon tea, and everything exceeded our expectations. The coffee was rich and expertly prepared, and the afternoon tea was beautifully presented, with a perfect selection of sandwiches, scones, and pastries. What made the experience truly special was the impeccable service — attentive, warm, and thoughtful without ever feeling intrusive. Every detail was handled with care, making our visit truly memorable. We can’t wait to return.

I had high hopes for the food and thought it would be really good but it was just "ok" l had a the set menu but regardless of this the food could have been better. The goulash lacked flavour and the cauliflower soup was just like eatting a bowl of fatty cream. The waitress also kept coming over to try and take our bowls when we had not finished to the point that l had to say... "are we slow eaters?" the decor is beautiful but the price of the food isn't justified. My desert was £13 and l would have got better from Mark's and Spencers.

My first time at The Wolseley in Piccadilly. I took a friend to lunch there, as a birthday treat. It’s a lovely restaurant, with a Viennese feel to the food and décor. We were sat at a window seat, and the whole experience was high quality. The food was wonderful, the staff were friendly and attentive, and the restaurant had a very nice atmosphere. I especially enjoyed the kedgeree. We will definitely return in the near future.

Had breakfast here very recently. My second visit but the first for my friends who loved the decor and atmosphere.
My only slight issue was that the waitress, spoke very quietly, didnt explain well and misunderstood one of our orders.
Although a minor issue we would definitely return, a real gem.
You must book ahead to get youf preferred timings.

4.5/5 - this is my dream atmosphere, hands down. My husband gave his food a 3.5 but I gave mine a 4.5 so we settled on 4.

Lovely teas, coffee, and it's a great spot to have breakfast. Their prices are changed from when I took the menu picture but that's the gist of their options!

name: Bill's Covent Garden Restaurant
address: St Martin's Courtyard, Slingsby Pl, London WC2H 9EF, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Contemporary European chain dishing up separate breakfast, afternoon tea, lunch and dinner menus.

details.formatted_address: St Martin's Courtyard, Slingsby Pl, London WC2H 9EF, UK
details.name: Bill's Covent Garden Restaurant

reviews.text: The restaurant has a very nice vibe. I really did like it. But the food is not worth the price. The steak is chewy. The hummus and bread was nice but not enough bread. Plenty of Gluten Free options. So I would recommend it for celiacs because we do not have many choices. But the food is not anything to write home about. The pancakes were chewy as well but it's the type of texture I like. It was good with the extra strawberry ice-cream but on its own with the fruits and the syrup. It's not worth it. There are definitely better restaurants to get steaks at. This is not one.

Bills - Covent Garden, Monday 27 January 2025. We chose this place to celebrate my daughter’s graduation. We were a party of 12. The service was impeccable from start to finish. Staff were accommodating but the star of the day is our server, Anna! She was gracious and accommodating, ensuring every aspect of our dining experience was perfect. This restaurant strikes the perfect balance between chic and cozy. The ambiance is trendy yet comfortable, making it ideal for intimate dinners and lively gatherings. The food is excellent and portion sizes are great!

We had breakfast at Bill’s this morning, and it was absolutely incredible! The Eggs Benedict were perfectly prepared and full of flavor—definitely one of the best I’ve had in a long time. One of our friends couldn’t stop raving about the pancakes, even calling them “the best pancakes they’ve ever put in their mouth.” That’s high praise, and they were not wrong!

The ambiance was cozy and welcoming, making it the perfect spot to start the day. The staff was attentive and friendly, which added to the experience.

If you’re planning to visit, I highly recommend making a reservation in advance to secure a table—it gets busy, and for good reason. Whether you’re a local or just visiting, Bill’s is a must-try for breakfast lovers. We can’t wait to return!

A Gem for Food Lovers… and Their Dogs!

Last night, we discovered this restaurant and honestly… what a gem! Everything was perfect: delicious, generous, full of flavor – a real treat for the taste buds. But what really makes it stand out is the exceptional hospitality, not only for us but also for our dog.

Yes, you read that right: our dog was treated like royalty! A water bowl as soon as we sat down, petting, care, and real warmth… It’s clear that animals are not just “tolerated” here, they are genuinely welcomed. And that’s rare and precious.

If you’re looking for a place to eat well, feel at home, and share the moment with your furry companion, go ahead and dive in. This restaurant is a real treasure we wholeheartedly recommend!

Amazing restaurant, warm and hospitable, with an excellent variety of dishes. Some dishes are original and sooo good! We can’t wait to come here every time we visit London! On a more practical note, the prices are very reasonable, waiting time is not long even without a reservation (the sign at the entrance says: No reservation? No problem. We’ll squish you in 😄). Today I went for brunch with my daughters and we were served by wonderful Kristin :) Thank you, Kristine 🌸💕 🙏🏻

editorial_summary.overview: 19th-century, French patisserie and tea rooms with marble-topped tables, plus art gallery spaces.

reviews.text: One of the best scone I have ever had. The scone itself was very nice, the jam was sweet as it is and the clotted cream was good. With black tea with milk was amazing. Oh the service there was abit rough and soso.😁

It was the best scone I've ever had. The combination of strawberry jam and clotted cream was perfect. ❤️
There were a lot of people,
Fortunately, I was able to sit down and eat.
The inside is a bit small and there are a lot of people, so it was better to eat outside. The scones from last year are still unforgettable.

A lovely bakery in the heart of Soho. I love the aesthetic old school environment you get to experience that is very different from most of the other cafes in London. The staff is welcoming and very friendly. I always take their recommendations and try something new every time I go.

This is my favourite place to enjoy tasty desserts and an espresso. This is the place I take all of my friends to, when they're visiting me in London.
My Korean friend took me to this place, it feels super local! I really loved the scones here, they were delicious and very reasonably priced. The coffee was great too.

Maison Bertaux in London was an absolute gem I discovered during my solo trip last year. If you're looking for a quintessential English tea and scones experience, this is the place to be. From the moment I stepped inside, I felt transported to a classic, charming tearoom. The atmosphere is warm and inviting, perfect for a relaxing afternoon treat.

The star of the show, of course, was the tea and scones. Everything tasted incredibly fresh and homemade. The scones were perfectly crumbly and buttery, and the clotted cream and jam were the perfect accompaniments. Paired with a steaming pot of tea, it was the ideal way to indulge in a traditional English afternoon tea. There was a bit of a wait when I visited, which is a testament to its popularity, but it was absolutely worth it.
Maison Bertaux offers a truly authentic and delightful experience. The combination of delicious treats, charming atmosphere, and classic English charm makes it a must-visit for anyone looking for a memorable afternoon tea in London. I highly recommend it and would gladly wait in line again for another taste of their wonderful scones.

editorial_summary.overview: Serene destination with a chic vibe offering a creative menu of Mediterranean dishes.

reviews.text:
I do love Ottolenghi. This time we had lunch in the Islington restaurant and, as always, it was an absolute delight.
Healthy and yummy food, great service and quite reasonably priced. Definitely recommend this place!

It’s always a pleasure looking at Ottolenghi window display of their beautiful salad platters and assortments of cakes and pastries. For lunch, I ordered the selection of 2 salad and salmon as mains. Food was cold, if you prefer it that way. We ordered the carrot cake and pain au chocolate for desserts and enjoyed it. The ambiance is lovely and we were told that they had just renovated. Service is good.

The food here was absolutely delicious m, and I can see why it is so highly revered. The service was also good and the staff were friendly and helpful.
I especially recommend getting the delicious desserts from the bar- they were all great.

The only reasons that I’ve given 4 stars are 1:  The atmosphere is pretty poor, and I hate the concept of their “long table”- it is just uncomfortable and weird to have to sit directly next to random strangers.
2: The price is really, really high for the level of dining experience- when I first walked in, I though, ‘£18 or so for a main, seems fully reasonable’, but when you are told that they are all starters and they recommend 2 dishes per person, I think this renders the price a bit unreasonable.
As always with an Ottolenghi creation, this too is a delightful culinary experience. Unfortunately I wasn’t too hungry so I only tried the labaneh and the aubergine, both delicious!

My visit to Ottolenghi in Islington was pretty disappointing. The food was served cold and honestly tasted like something you’d get at a school cafeteria. It didn’t have much flavor, and it definitely wasn’t worth the high prices. I’m surprised people say it’s so great because you can easily find the exact same food at the grocery store, probably even fresher and cheaper. I think the place is overhyped and doesn’t match up to all the good things people say about it.

editorial_summary.overview: Traditional boozer with oak-panelled booths, on both sides of street joined by underground cellar.

reviews.text: Lovely pub only pub that is on both sides of the road staff very friendly very professional clean tidy represented nice range of beers sorry can't give a review for food as I'm only there for the beer 🍺🍻
Perfect pub for lunch. The fish and chips were actually wonderful! The service was not friendly but probably because I’m an obvious tourist. I recommend the stop still!
Great little pub. Managed to get a seat and had a couple of drinks. The atmosphere was good and drinks resonably priced for London. Lots of choice and room to stand out the front

The ship & Shovel is a must.
Present on a Friday evening at 7:00pm.
There is not a singular structure housing the pub. You shall see when you get here but both sides are a vibe, you just have to dive in and select your destination. The right or the left, are you feeling like the right piece of grilled cheese or the left piece? Divided down the middle by the bar buddies congregating in the Craven Passage, here you will find a delicious lager: the Ship & Shovel: hells lager. After drinking a Crisp, clean, light-bodied, hint of lemony lager you become immersed in the British pub culture surrounded by accents, beer and friendly banter. Highly recommend, cheers to your first pint!

My boyfriend insisted on us seeing this pub and it definitely lived up to the hype. Really cool history throughout while maintaining a fun casual vibe. Although the outside looks busy it’s still very easy to get a drink.

editorial_summary.overview: Free-entry art galleries hosting world-renowned temporary exhibitions on either side of the lake.

reviews.text:
A favourite gallery of mine that I have been visiting for the last 40+ years
Free entry with always fascinating and inspiring shows. A great bookshop and toilets too which are handy. Always worth a visit, accompanied by a walk through the beautiful park!

Serpentine Gallery has an exciting programme of well curated exhibitions and events, free entry!
It sits in the middle of the park in the middle of Central London, and it has two branches, Serpentine North and South. The exhibitions sometimes take over areas of the park as in this current one with Penone

A nice gallery in the heart of the park! I had an opportunity to see the Suspended States gallery. All sections were incredible! The sanctuary city was quite interesting with the attention to details of each building! The war library presentation was also fascinating.

The book store also had a great selection of books both old and new from various categories.

Nice exhibition friendly staff with two free galleries in the park. One was closed as it was winter but will be opening again for summer the staff said with  something nice for children too :) will visit again

Fabulous gallery tucked away in Hyde Park, a short walk from Queensway to the north and Albert memorial to the south. The Serpentine Gallery always has a quirky or idiosyncratic installation or exhibition to feed the mind or trigger debate. As always it is a good idea to check the opening times to avoid disappointment.

name: Curzon Bloomsbury
address: The Brunswick Centre, London WC1N 1AW, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Small arthouse cinema, focused on independent films, with underground screens and bar.

details.formatted_address: The Brunswick Centre, London WC1N 1AW, UK
details.name: Curzon Bloomsbury

reviews.text:
It was my first time in this cinema. It was a disappointment. It costs £18.5 for non-members and the seat was small and not comfortable and without a cup holder. Although the seats can change angles. It was still uncomfortable as it kept slipping back. The projector was placed in a low position as people could block the projector when they walked past.

There were also very limited Gluten-free options for the food.

One thing that I really liked was the amount of break out space that is available. Although I preferred they make the cinema room bigger than the amount of break out space.

Awesome staff there.
My partner and I went there yet the film we wanted to see was sold out.   The girl at the till was really nice to try to sort it out for us and gave us good advice to see another film which turned out to be great.  Lovely experience.

This review is for the Membership, rather than for the cinema itself.  Sorry Curzon Bloomsbury to give you this review, you are a lovely cinema, with good customer service, but it's the only way that I can make this complaint in a way that has any impact.  This year, I didn't use up all of my free cinema tickets that are the primary benefit of the membership.  When the membership expired, I received an email to say that my membership would auto renew, or if I wanted to cancel, I should email and ask for it to not renew.  Because I hadn't used up all of my tickets, I evaluated that there was no point renewing, as I wasn't going to the cinema enough to justify the membership.  What I was not told in any part of this communication was that the free ticket entitlement that I still had, would also expire, and I think 2 or 3 tickets would be lost.  Had I known this, I would have made sure to use up these tickets.  But it was not made clear.  I think that it would be normal to allow these tickets to roll over until they were used, or, to give a 1 month period to allow the customer to use them up, but it is not okay to not give a warning that they will expire if the member doesn't renew.  I think this is a very mean and mercenary practice and will not rejoin this cinema chain even if I start visiting more.  Very disappointed customer, who feels that something that I paid for and believe I was entitled to, was taken away by a sneaky business practice.

I absolutely love the programme in Curzon cinemas and have had memberships on and off for the past 20 years. Bloomsbury in particular has amazing selection of movies and documentaries.

However, management, can you please do something about keeping clean the cafe/ bar area? I do get that evenings before screenings can get busy but it's so hard to find a table without having to clear off the used cups and bottles and glasses yourself - and when I asked the bar lady to come do it, she just took everything away but left all tables dirty and wet :( Definitely won't be spending time here again before screening - very unappealing. :( Some of the upholstery could do with a clean too.

Enjoyed this very much. The drinks are a little higher priced than I’m used to but that was alright. Saw a preview for Flow with a q&a with the director in a beautiful, comfortable screen so I can be thankful for that.

editorial_summary.overview: Antipodean-style independent cafe in cool Berwick Street Market, serving artisan coffee and snacks.

reviews.text: Coffee is nice, this coffee was nice. Was pleasantly surprised by the option of almond milk as well as oat you don’t always get that. Quick with their service perfectly nice to sit in and sip. Cakes and bites looked quite nice even through I didn’t try.

A really cool coffee shop in Soho with a vibrant, energetic vibe. They play great music, and I enjoyed a creamy flat white along with a perfectly flaky and buttery croissant.

The staff was very friendly, adding to the relaxed atmosphere. This spot isn’t quiet—the music is loud, making it ideal if you’re looking for a place with energy and good tunes while enjoying your coffee. Perfect for a lively break!

Not your average hipster coffee shop. Tucked away on Berwick Street in the heart of Soho, Flat White has an unassuming exterior and a no-fuss, functional interior. Black walls, hanging filament bulbs, and a cluttered counter stacked with grinders, pastries, and milk alternatives—it’s pure organised chaos, in the best possible way.

But it’s the staff and the coffee that make this place sing. The atmosphere is loud—thrashing metal music on full blast—which, while it was a bit much, it was nothing a good pair of ANC headphones couldn’t fix.

Now, I love my coffee strong, and their iced oat latte absolutely delivered. While you’re at it, grab yourself a ‘Good ol’ chocolate chip cookie’ (yes, that’s the actual name) or one of the pain au chocolats piled up at the counter.

Settle yourself on one of the benches out front and watch Soho life unfold around you. A staple, no-frills, thrilling coffee experience that gets straight to the point.
Good coffee, no sandwiches, just some pastries that are available during the time of visit. Banana bread was good.
Cool spot, good looking food. The coffee was insanely good. Possibly the beat coffee ive had. Id like to know what beans they use so I can have at home. Will be back for sure.

editorial_summary.overview: Small bites with artisan coffees made using beans sourced directly from exporters and roasted daily.

reviews.text: While exploring Redchurch Street for my blog, I took a break at Allpress for a delicious latte and a sticky cinnamon bun. It’s easily one of my favourite coffee spots in London!

I think I have found my new favourite coffee spot. The iced mocha was okay, not the worst drink I’ve ever had but I definitely won’t be getting it again.
Their iced latte with oat milk and brown sugar syrup is delicious!
The servers are really nice and welcoming and I definitely need to try their almond croissant.

Edit:
I finally tried their almond croissant, it was superb!  However, I felt like it had too much filling.

Great coffee shop on Redchurch street! They have great indoor and outdoor seating, we like to sip our flat whites outside. The espresso is tasty and well made. The service is quick and friendly. We always stop here when we are in the neighborhood!

The girl at the counter was nice but £4.40 for a regular hot chocolate? Plus it was served in a small paper cup (eating in) because they were closing in 30'... they don't have toilets and the place is tiny to sit down. I understand it's in the heart of Shoreditch but still very pricey for the poor service

I was sitting outside with my baby. I left the table for a minute to change the baby’s nappy. When I tried to go back to my table someone from the staff removed our drinks and told us we had to leave, as they were going to close. We were the only ones kick out. The rest of customers were able to stay… it felt very strange and rude. I will never come back, even when this is my favourite coffee in shoreditch.

editorial_summary.overview: Vast, bohemian indoor market hosting an eclectic range of antiques, vintage and retro stalls.

reviews.text:
Overall nice experience but be mindful of certain stalls. My boyfriend and I visited here today, hoping to find a Chinese-style plate as a Christmas gift for his mum. Unfortunately, I can’t say it was an entirely pleasant experience.

The shopping experience on the ground floor was lovely. Beth Adams gave us a warm welcome at her charming little shop and shared the fascinating stories behind her items.

However, things took a sour turn on the first floor. We spotted a Chinese plate at a stall located next to a lighting shop. If I’m not mistaken, the stall’s name includes “Yang,” and its number might be FO16.

We asked the gentleman nearby for more details. He claimed it was from the Qing Dynasty and told us the stall owner was away. He kindly offered to call her, which we appreciated. From the call, we learned that the plate was from the 18th century and priced at £120.

The plate was in a display case, so we couldn’t examine it closely. The gentleman offered to take it out, but we didn’t let him do so at the beginning as I had the doubt and didn’t want to waste his time. But later on we kindly asked him to take it out cause my boyfriend really liked it, taking it out would allow us to inspect the bottom, which is crucial for assessing its value especially when there was no further information from the owner. However, he seemed overly keen to seal the sale. After viewing the underside shortly, we grew more doubtful of its authenticity and decided not to buy it. His response? “Oh, so you’re not buying it?” Sounds like we have to buy it because he took it out. A £120 plate isn’t a five-quid trinket, it’s not something I’d buy after just a glance behind a glass case and even grew more doubts after checking it.

As we were leaving, he insisted on ringing the stallholder again, despite us having no further questions. The gentleman then asked, “Are you Chinese?” and told me to speak to the stallholder in Mandarin. I was completely taken aback. When she heard I was Chinese, her attitude turned hostile, saying, “I’m not here to educate you about the item.”

As a Chinese person, I feel obliged to warn others interested in Chinese porcelain to tread carefully. Many antique plates are replicas, so unless you’re an expert able to assess value from behind a glass case, steer clear of stallholders unwilling to share essential information especially all the other shop owners we met today were literally expecting us to ask something. But of course I would never say it’s 100% replica, I’m not a pro.

But thanks to Moe from the N&S Watches, which is absolutely a gem in the market. He is so kind with patience, I picked up a lovely antique watch in his shop before leaving, at least I didn’t leave feeling frustrated!

Huge mall full of individual antique stores. As always with these places, the stall owners are pretty snotty, unapproachable and dusty old people that make the experience of looking around less enjoyable than you might hope. It’s seemingly an issue with the whole industry but you feel it when walking round this cavernous building replete with expensive bric a brac. The best thing you can do, is to take some brief relief in the rooftop cafe which is probably the only place you’ll find a bargain price in the whole market.
It’s like time traveling. Great stuff to look at but prices are extremely high. Not for the common person
Very friendly welcome, lots of interesting stalls and many beautiful objects. Lots of vintage clothes and jewellery. Well worth a visit.

There is such a unique, authentic atmosphere in here that has been lost by all other markets in London. With its winding corridors and ancient stairs, it feels like walking through a Harry Potter movie set.

I could get lost in here for hours exploring and examining the stalls and talking with the charming owners and observing the interesting people.

And to top it all of - the cafe on the top floor which also opens to a beautiful rooftop terrace is divine. With VERY reasonably priced food and homemade cake!

editorial_summary.overview: European food and cocktails in smart spot with monochrome floor tiles, feature lighting and terrace.

reviews.text: Popped here as a lunch treat for my mother. Excellent venue and, for the quality of the food, very keenly priced. Lovely fresh food, and the surroundings are great - there are tables for board games and newspapers in one part. Very efficient and friendly service and loos to DIE for! Fabulous way to spend an afternoon.

We had the set menu which was delicious! We had cheddar veloute, salmon maki, gnocchi, pie and sticky toffee pudding! With a glass of prosecco on the side. We will definitely be returning! All food was absolutely delicious. Staff were attentive and the venue was beautiful!

Bluebird is definitely DOG FRIENDLY. My dog was pretty chill in the restaurant. She felt welcome by the friendly staff. There was a whippet as well. The restaurant is listed in the Dog-Friendly Chelsea Map which shows the shops and restaurants  welcoming dogs.

I possibly had the best Sunday Roast ever. Yes, it's more expensive than ordinary pubs. The rump steak was so tender, moist and flavourful. A generous portion of roast vegetables accompanied the rump steak and a giant crispy Yorkshire pudding. The roast potatoes were so delicious and crispy. (Forget about the calories 😀). My dog also liked the seasonal vegetables 😀 After finishing the whole plate, my tummy had no room for dessert. I will go back to try the roast pork next time.

The perfect spot for a Sunday roast! ⭐️
Make sure you book a table in advance ❤️
The staff was very kind and helpful 🥰 food was great but definitely on the pricey side!
The burger was 10/10 and the Sunday roast was amazing (the chicken is quite popular)! 🤩
A lovely spot for brunch with a beautiful terrace, attentive service, and delicious food. I also visited for dinner — it had a great vibe with good music, making it perfect for a relaxed evening out.

editorial_summary.overview: English and American breakfasts, plus comfort foods and burgers in cheerful, quirky surrounds.

reviews.text:
These guys get their food straight out of a movie post. Look and flavor wise, it was amazing, especially considering the prices are not insane for the London environment.

Do take into account that we came at 10:15 on a Tuesday and 10 minutes after we sat down (no queue for us), the space was full as they don’t have a lot of tables, maybe 12 in total.

Staff were super friendly and the food came quickly, we’ll be back!

The best pancakes we have ever had in our whole entire lives. Enjoyed it very much. The savoury breakfast was also very good. The portions were very generous. Loved it. Would definitely go back and recommend to those who are into breakfast/brunch.😄

Went here for Sunday brunch with friends. Although there was a 20 minute queue outside, we stood in the shade and were entertained by the engaging Louie. Food was lovely, great portion sizes for a reasonable price. Excellent decor as well. Would definitely visit again!

Decent place to have a breakfast but does not have anything special, food was fine but a bit tasteless. Avoid breakfast club sandwitch, nothing special. The service was iind with us and we waited only 10’ outside. The price is a bit high for the food quality. I’d say its a bit american brunch rather than classic brunch but with british breakfast plates.
We loved it. Vanilla latte was perfectly sweet. The breakfast was really tasty. Recommended! It’s a great place to start a day.

editorial_summary.overview: Breakfast-to-dinner British fare served in a bright, modern space.

reviews.text: Beautiful cafe with a lovely secluded outdoor seating area. Outdoor seating is under large canopies with heaters. Indoor seating is lovely and open with an open kitchen at the back. Service was fantastic, we waited only a couple of minutes for a table. Food was really good. We had the eggs royale and brunch waffles. Both were brilliant, really tasty and decent size portions. The ice chai latte was also so good, like a milkshake! Seems to be popular so would recommend booking if you really want to come.

A Gem in Southwark for Breakfast Lovers!

I had such a great experience at Table Restaurant — definitely one of the best breakfast spots in the area. The food is genuinely excellent, with fresh ingredients and generous portions that really hit the spot. From the classics to the more creative options, everything we tried was delicious and well-prepared.

What really stood out was the staff incredibly attentive, friendly, and welcoming from the moment we walked in. It’s clear they take pride in what they do and it adds so much to the overall vibe of the place. Highly recommend if you're looking for a quality breakfast in a relaxed, down-to-earth setting. Will absolutely be back!

Wonderful brunch cafe. They have delicious pancake and burger options but I opted for the egg dishes. The eggs florentine was wonderful - great to dtart your day with. The prices are reasonable considering the location and food quality.

I would recommend booking in advance. We didn’t book, but were lucky to get seated. If we came at a different time, we might’ve not have gotten as lucky.

A negative are the seats/tables. It feels very squished inside, which was unpleasant. Felt like I was talking over other people.

Really great service and friendly staff, fair prices. Food was not bad but also not that great. Definitely tasted better egg Benedict. Also if you order the iced tea prepare for it to be incredibly sweet, maybe a little too sweet. There was no line for a weekday breakfast.

100% worth a visit. We had a booking for 11AM and it was quite busy - it took us some time to be seated and it wasn't clear where we needed to wait. The food was amazing and the coffee matched the quality. Despite how busy it was the vibes were good and it wasn't loud or hectic and it was really easy to enjoy our meal. The staff were kind and attentive with the exception that we had to wait a fair bit longer than is ideal to ask for the bill.

name: Ev Restaurant
address: The Arches, 98 Isabella St, London SE1 8DD, UK

editorial_summary.overview: Classic Turkish mezze dishes and grilled meats, in a comfortable eatery under the railway arches.

details.formatted_address: The Arches, 98 Isabella St, London SE1 8DD, UK
details.name: Ev Restaurant

reviews.text:
Came here wanting drinks and dessert. It’s large and spacious which is nice. Unfortunately there are specific seating areas depending on what you want. Tableside service should generally be given where you sit. We were asked to move tables just because we wanted dessert only.

We received a cold reception from the first waiter, and were directed to another section of the restaurant. The second person to help us with dessert directed us to a deli style fridge with a small selection of desserts and salads on display in the same fridge. He looked irritated that he had to help us and was rather unwelcoming.

Quality of food and drinks were disappointing. Desserts were unfortunately true to the display as they didn’t taste fresh and lacked taste. Hot chocolate was extremely watered down with minimal hot chocolate and more foam than anything else, estimating a ratio of 30% foam.

Quality of service and food where definite lows with much room for improvement.

Grilled lamb steak was nice - tasted good and was tender. Prawns were also good. The lamb shank was falling off the bone but it was lacking flavour. The food was okay but compared to other Turkish restaurants I’ve been to, I was a little underwhelmed and kind of wished I’d gone to one of those (sorry).

The cocktails were lovely though and our waiter was attentive. My companion asked if they could make me some sort of traditional cocktail and they did, which was lovely. Not many people eating at the restaurant when we visited so very quiet.

Booked a table, however we weren’t able to pick the table we wanted even though the restaurant was literally empty on a weekend morning.
Overpriced food for what it is. There are certainly better options.

Delicious Turkish food with spectacular ambience. My wife and I shared the Domates Soslu Kofte, Zeytinli Salata, Hellim and Acokadolu Ispanak Salatasi. Everything was amazing and along with the quiet low rumbling of the train overhead made for a very pleasant experience. I absolutely recommend this restaurant and will definitely return next time we are in London.

Beautifully decorated, excellent service, food very good.
A big restaurant well looked after for the staff members. Just next door they have got a large room for parties not compromising the nice atmosphere of the restaurant.
Easy access for wheelchairs.
Only 10 minutes away from Waterloo Station. As I was in a hurry to catch the train I decided to do a take away & they game me a nice pot & bag. Today was part of my lunch and was delicious Will go back for more 😀

editorial_summary.overview: Traditional rooms in a pair of 1880s townhouses with a casual cafe, plus free breakfast and Wi-Fi.

reviews.text:
Wonderful stay. Run by a service oriented family. The staff is lovely. Continental breakfast is fresh, even freshly baked croissants! And you can order cooked to order eggs and accompaniments.

Location is excellent. A few minutes walk from Earl’s Court. Room size was perfect. Didn’t feel tiny. Lovely kettle in the room and mini bar. As a solo traveler I felt very safe. Excellent noise blocking doors as well.

I’d definitely return and recommend staying here!

We had the pleasure of staying at London Lodge Hotel for 3 nights. We were curious whether the reviews were right or if they were too good to be true. It was even better than expected.
